<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-713-419  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 713 419.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer  Dec 1990 v23 n12 p13(11).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Do parallel languages respond to the needs of scientificprogrammers?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pancake, Cherri M.; Bergmark, Donna.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Existing languages do not provide enough support for scientificprogramming and it is the responsibility of computer scientists tounderstand the needs and expectations of the user community anddevelop ways to help develop parallel applications.andP;  Scientificprogrammers use sequential techniques to study the physical worldthey model.andP;  These users are not concerned about the effects ofconcurrency, they want to use the computational power provided bymultiple processors.andP;  Scientific programmers see nondeterminacy asundesirable, not as a property to be explored.andP;  The difficulty ofreformulating sequential code hampers many applications fromtaking advantage of multiprocessing capabilities.andP;  Scientificprogrammers use language extensions or runtime libraries forlanguage support because of the availability of production-levelcomputers, familiarity, and apparent ease that sequential programscan be parallelized using extensions or libraries.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Scientific ResearchProgrammingParallel ProcessingProgramming LanguagesMultiprocessing.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartprogram.andO;Caption:   Problem-solution system. (chart)Example of conceptual solution for satellite control. (chart)Algorithmic solution for one portion of the satellite example.andO;(program)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>